---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import rankings from '../data/rankings.json';

// B9: honest build date + per-signal vintages emitted by the pipeline.
// Coded defensively so the page still renders against pre-regen data.
type Vintages = {
  matrix?: { source: string; note: string };
  gdp?: { series: string; label: string; selection: string; years: string; modalYear: number };
  arrivals?: { series: string; label: string; window: string; preferredYear: number; yearsUsed: string };
  migrants?: { series: string; label: string; selection: string; years: string; modalYear: number };
  hdi?: { source: string; year: number };
};
const meta = rankings as typeof rankings & { builtAt?: string; vintages?: Vintages };
const builtAt = meta.builtAt ?? (meta as { generatedAt?: string }).generatedAt ?? '';
const v = meta.vintages ?? {};
---
<Base title="Methodology — Pyatkov Index" description="The formula, data sources, and per-signal data vintages behind the Pyatkov Index.">
  <p class="kicker">Protocol · How the score is computed</p>
  <h1>Methodology</h1>

  <h2>The idea</h2>
  <p>
    Classic passport indexes count destinations: visa-free access to a micronation is worth exactly as much
    as visa-free access to the United States. The Pyatkov Index weights every destination by how valuable
    access to it actually is, so weak destinations fade toward zero and strong destinations dominate.
  </p>

  <h2>Destination weights</h2>
  <p>Each of the {rankings.totalDestinations} destinations gets a weight from four signals:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GDP</strong> (World Bank, current US$) — log-scaled</li>
    <li><strong>International tourism, number of arrivals</strong> (World Bank / UN Tourism series
      <code>ST.INT.ARVL</code>) — log-scaled. This counts arrivals of non-resident visitors and mixes
      overnight tourists with same-day visitors, with definitions varying by country; it is a proxy for
      how much the world travels to a destination, not a pure tourist count.</li>
    <li><strong>HDI</strong> (UNDP Human Development Report) — used on its natural scale</li>
    <li><strong>International migrant stock, total</strong> (World Bank, series <code>SM.POP.TOTL</code>)
      — log-scaled</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Every signal is put on one common scale — a population <em>z-score</em> (how many standard deviations
    above or below the destination average it sits), computed only over the destinations that actually
    report that signal. GDP, arrivals, and migrant stock are logged first because they span several orders
    of magnitude; HDI is already a bounded index and is z-scored on its natural scale. A destination's
    composite <code>Z</code> is the mean of whichever z-scores it has (a missing signal is simply left out
    of the mean, never imputed off-scale).
  </p>
  <p>
    The weight is then a tempered exponential of that composite: <code>weight = exp(1.25 × Z)</code>. The
    exponential is what lets destination <em>quality</em> genuinely dominate <em>count</em> — one composite
    standard deviation of extra value is worth about <code>exp(1.25) ≈ 3.5×</code> more weight — so a handful
    of strong destinations (Germany, Japan, the United States) outweigh dozens of weak ones, while the score
    stays smooth, strictly monotonic in value, and bounded.
  </p>

  <h2>Access credit</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Visa-free / freedom of movement — <strong>1.0</strong></li>
    <li>Visa on arrival / eTA — <strong>0.8</strong></li>
    <li>eVisa — <strong>0.5</strong></li>
    <li>Visa required / no admission — <strong>0</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The score</h2>
  <p>
    <code>score = 100 × Σ credit(passport, d) × weight(d) / Σ weight(d)</code>, where <strong>both</strong>
    sums run over every destination <em>including the passport's own country</em>, which every passport
    admits visa-free (credit 1.0). A country's own destination value therefore accrues to its own score, so
    large, high-value home economies (the United States most of all, since it is the single most valuable
    destination) rank higher than they would if their own weight were thrown away. Because numerator and
    denominator cover the same full pool, a passport with full visa-free access still scores exactly 100, and
    the score reads as "percent of the world's destination value this passport can reach." The <strong>Count
    rank</strong> is the ranking you get from the same graded credits over the same full set of destinations
    but with every destination worth 1 — a plain "how many places can you go" count. The <strong>Δ vs
    count</strong> column is the gap between the two, so a passport that reaches disproportionately valuable
    destinations rises and one skewed toward low-value destinations falls.
  </p>

  <h2>Sources &amp; data vintages</h2>
  <p>
    Visa matrix: the open
    <a href="https://github.com/imorte/passport-index-data">passport-index-data</a> dataset
    (the maintained successor to the archived <code>ilyankou/passport-index-dataset</code>, PassportIndex.org
    data). Economic and social signals: the World Bank API and UNDP Human Development Report downloads.
    A few passport-issuing entities absent from those sources (Taiwan, Vatican City, and North Korea in part)
    use hand-researched values documented in the repository. The {rankings.totalDestinations} destinations are
    sovereign states and SARs; dependent territories with their own visa regimes are out of scope, inherited
    from the upstream dataset.
  </p>
  {meta.vintages && (
    <Fragment>
      <p>
        Because the four signals carry different observation years, we disclose each one's vintage rather than
        a single snapshot label:
      </p>
      <ul class="vintages">
        {v.matrix && <li><strong>Visa matrix</strong>: {v.matrix.source} — {v.matrix.note}</li>}
        {v.gdp && <li><strong>{v.gdp.label}</strong> (<code>{v.gdp.series}</code>): {v.gdp.selection}, years {v.gdp.years} (modal {v.gdp.modalYear})</li>}
        {v.arrivals && <li><strong>{v.arrivals.label}</strong> (<code>{v.arrivals.series}</code>): {v.arrivals.window} window, preferring {v.arrivals.preferredYear}; years used {v.arrivals.yearsUsed}</li>}
        {v.migrants && <li><strong>{v.migrants.label}</strong> (<code>{v.migrants.series}</code>): {v.migrants.selection}, years {v.migrants.years} (modal {v.migrants.modalYear})</li>}
        {v.hdi && <li><strong>HDI</strong>: {v.hdi.source}, reference year {v.hdi.year}</li>}
      </ul>
    </Fragment>
  )}
  <p>
    Built {builtAt} — the date the pipeline last ran, not the vintage of any single signal. All raw data and
    code are in the repo; the entire index is reproducible with one command.
  </p>
</Base>
